2. Moving average¶

We will simply take the mean of the last 24 hours data to predict the next hour.

  • Pros:
    • Lower computation.
    • Good for business decision which does not require much precision.
  • Cons
    • Lower precision
    • There will still be unexplained variance.
    • The seasonality attribute of the data is not explained.

2. SARIMA¶

  • p: The number of lag observations included in the model, also called the lag order.
  • d: The number of times that the raw observations are differenced, also called the degree of differencing.
  • q: The size of the moving average window, also called the order of moving average.

So, here I will create two manipulated dataframes :¶

  1. will have lag comsumptions of exactly (hourwise) 2 days before, 7 days before and 365 days before.
  2. the other dataframe will have the comsumption like the first dataframe but will have all the hours in the subject day.

Here our data will shrink a little however we will be able to create a model that understands the seasonality.

Also, we will have the opportunity to use the other variables, which we were unable to.

Then, I will perform different regression algorithms.¶

Because of the time constraint I will perform Linear Regression and Decision Tree.¶

df_second=df_weather.copy()

# hour lagging
for hour in range(24):
    df_second["two_day_{}hour_lag".format(hour)]=df_second["Consumption"].shift(24*2-hour)

# week lagging
for hour in range(24):
    df_second["week_{}hour_lag".format(hour)]=df_second["Consumption"].shift(24*7-hour)

# year lagging
for hour in range(24):
    df_second["year_{}hour_lag".format(hour)]=df_second["Consumption"].shift(24*365-hour)

for temps in ["T_1","T_2","T_3","T_4","T_5","T_6","T_7"]:
    df_second["previous_"+temps]=df_second[temps].shift(48)
df_second=df_second.dropna().reset_index(drop=True)

Playing on the real data's features:¶

  1. Here we see that the features starting with "T" has a high correlation. With 90% confidence we concluded that the features are all the same. Correlation image from the profiling page here. To generalize our models we will drop these columns but one.

  2. We will have 2 years unlike 3 years in the original data. The gap year is işlendi to the original data. I will feed the year as categorical variable to the models.

  3. Months,Day, and Hour will be fed as categorical variable. Regarding the performance, I will change this variables to becomes sinusodial waves. (Becoming cyclic motions)

  4. We will add weekday as categoric variable.
